===Etymology===
< {{etyl|enm}} {{term|talent|lang=enm}} < {{etyl|fro}} {{term|talent|lang=fro||a talent, also will, inclination, desire}} < {{etyl|la|en}} {{term|talentum||a Grecian weight; a talent of money|lang=la}} < {{etyl|grc|en}} {{term|τάλαντον||balance, a particular weight, esp. of gold, sum of money, a talent|tr=talanton|lang=grc|sc=polytonic}}. The figurative meanings 2. and 3. come from Matt. XXV 14-30.

===Pronunciation===
* {{audio|En-us-talent.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# a [[unit]] of [[weight]] and [[money]] used in [[ancient]] times in Greece, the Roman Empire, and the Middle East.
# a marked [[ability]] or [[skill]].
#: ''He has the '''talent''' of touching his nose with his tongue.''
# the [[potential]] or [[factual]] [[ability]] to [[perform]] a [[skill]] [[better]] than most people.
#: ''She has a '''talent''' to sing.''
#: Also used jocularly, as: ''He has a '''talent''' for getting into trouble.''

